{
  "text": "Some data suggest that in addition to LTA, some other component(s) of the gram-positive bacterial wall may contribute directly or indirectly to the induction of i-NOS. Another bacterial wall component, peptidoglycan G, does not induce i-NOS but enhances greatly the effect of LTA [CITATION_1] . Bacterial serogroup polyosides of Streptococcus mutans OMZ 175 (rhamnose glucose polymers [RGPs] ) induce the release of several cytokines, including tumor necrosis factor alpha (TNF-\u2423) (3), which is known to be a powerful inducer of i-NOS activity [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
  "correct_citation": {
